'''Arthur Paul Harper''' {{post-nominals|country=NZL|CBE}} (27 June 1865 &ndash; 30 May 1955) was a New Zealand lawyer, mountaineer, explorer, businessman and  conservationist. He was simply known as '''AP''' or '''APH'''. He was born at his parents' house in Armagh Street, [[Christchurch]], New Zealand in 1865.<ref name="DNZB Harper">{{DNZB|Langton|Graham|4h17|Arthur Paul Harper|1 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Birth |url= http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=CHP18650628.2.6 |accessdate=4 October 2013 |newspaper=[[The Press]] |date=28 June 1865 |volume=VII |issue=830 |page=2}}</ref>

He was the son of the MP and lawyer [[Leonard Harper]]. Bishop [[Henry Harper (bishop)|Henry Harper]] was his grandfather.<ref name="DNZB Harper" />

In 1935, Harper was awarded the [[King George V Silver Jubilee Medal]].<ref>{{cite news | url= http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=EP19350506.2.12 | title=Official jubilee medals | date=6 May 1935 | volume=CXIX | issue=105 | newspaper=[[The Evening Post (New Zealand)|Evening Post]] | accessdate=17 June 2015 | page=4}}</ref> In the [[1952 New Year Honours (New Zealand)|1952 New Year Honours]] he was appointed a [[Order of the British Empire|Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] for services to the community.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=39423 |date=28 December 1951 |pages=41–43  |supp=y }}</ref> He died in Wellington in 1955.<ref name="DNZB Harper" />

